<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-064-294  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 064 294.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Jan 15 1990 n253 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer crime: an inside job. (internal computer securityprocedures and equipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fillon, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The 1989 Computer Security Survey by the accounting firm Ernst andamp;Young found that 23 percent of the 285 companies responding hadfinancial losses as a result of malicious acts in the previous twoyears, and 76 percent report that their organizations now maintainan information/computer security staff.andP;  Awareness of the need forimproved computer security measures is increasing, but executivesstill are not adept at dealing with it.andP;  FBI Dir William S.andO;Sessions told the 16th Annual Computer Security Conference inAtlanta in Nov 1989 that hardware and software vendors areresponsible along with users for the security of existing computersystems.andP;  RJ Milford Associates claims that 65 percent of allcomputer security breaches are caused by mistakes, and that onlythree percent are caused by outsiders; 16 percent are committed bydishonest employees and six percent by disgruntled employees.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data SecurityManagement of EDPPlanningOrganization StructureMISComputer CrimesSurvey.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>